An American-style capitalism of favoritism
Do you remember the East Asia crisis? When the U.S. Treasury Department and its IMF allies blamed the problems in this region on a capitalism of favoritism, lack of transparency, and an ineffective government?
Countries were encouraged to follow the American model, to use American accounting firms, and to introduce American entrepreneurs to teach them how to run their businesses.
It doesn't matter that under the leadership of its own entrepreneurs, East Asia developed more rapidly than any other region - and with greater stability - over the last three decades.
The growing Enron scandal brings new meaning to two well-known American proverbs: "You reap what you sow" and "Be perfect yourself before you criticize others."
Enron used large accounting strategies and complicated financial products (derivatives) to mislead investors about its value.
No transparency here.
It used its money to acquire influence and power, shape U.S. energy policy, and avoid regulations.
Favoritism-based capitalism is not new, nor is it the exclusive domain of one party.
The former U.S. Minister of Finance, Robert Rubin, would have tried to influence the current government to intervene on Enron's behalf in the controversial conflict in India.
When in office, he intervened when the accounting standards-setting office, supposedly independent, attempted to clean up the accounting of executive perks.
It was partly due to him that this effort to make corporate accounting more transparent was hindered.
The enthusiasm of America to bail out airlines with several billion dollars or to create cartels to protect its steel and aluminum industries suggests that the ideology of free market is just a thin veil for the benefit of old businesses: giving to those who have the right connections.
For some, the fact that Enron was not bailed out and that the problems were not revealed testifies to the absence of favoritism-based capitalism.
My interpretation is different: it testifies to the importance of a free press that may not stop abuses but can reduce them.
When the press began to look into Enron, the number of members of Congress who had accepted money from Enron was revealed.
Campaign contributions were not simply matters of public interest, but investments.
Like most of Enron's investments, everything went perfectly well in the short term, but did not yield results in the long term.
Several lessons can be drawn from this company.
Some concerning politics: the Enron scandal strengthens the arguments in favor of reforming campaign financing and the need for even more effective laws that must be disclosed to the public.
Democracies are undermined by business interests capable of buying elections.
However, the Bush administration refuses to disclose information that would attest to the role of business interests in shaping its energy policy.
Other lessons concern the economy, more specifically the economy of information.
For markets to function, for appropriate signals aiming to allocate resources efficiently to be provided, investors must receive as much information as possible.
There are inherent conflicts of interest: owners and managers are naturally motivated to present as rosy a picture as possible.
Accounting controls are intended to set limits on potential abuses.
But who will watch the watchers?
Who will control the accountants?
We rely heavily on motivations.
Accountants want to maintain their reputation.
But the relationship between advisory and accounting control practices leads to other perverted motivations: a motivation to please clients who do not appreciate unfavorable reports.
Arthur Levitt, the former chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, recognized the conflict: given that many within the accounting control firms focus on their own short-term interests, the integrity of controls could be compromised.
He is undoubtedly the unknown hero of the debacle.
But the accounting control firms and their corporate clients - which is no surprise, given the cabal that has developed - have strongly attacked his proposal to separate advisory and accounting control activities.
What Levitt understood - and that the Enron debacle has so clearly shown - is that motivations are important, but unimpeded markets cannot by themselves provide the best motivations.
Markets cannot provide motivations for the creation of wealth; they can provide motivations for the type of deals that Enron was implementing.
The new economy - and its new complicated financial instruments - highlight the problems of reliable accounting control structures; they make them easier to confuse.
Instead of facing the problems, American business systematically turns its back on them, supported and encouraged by American-style capitalism of favoritism.
The major problem of our time is to find the right balance between government and the market.
The status quo will claim that Enron is an exception: that its collapse was due to fraud, that we have laws against fraud, and that those who violate these laws must suffer the consequences and will suffer them.
But the majority of Enron's actions were legal.
Its auditors state that its core practices complied with the law and that thousands of other companies act in the same way.
They are right - and that is precisely the problem.
Investors need to be sure that the information they receive sufficiently reflects a company's economic situation.
Within the current regulatory and legal framework, with derivatives and other off-balance-sheet liabilities, investors currently have no possibility of being offered these guarantees.
We need better standards and more effective laws.
Although we will never be able to prevent all abuses, we can check the motivations.
We can attempt to instill better ethical standards.
But we cannot rely on them when so many people in the world find nothing wrong with the phenomenon of the "revolving door".
They claim to manage conflicts of interest, but we see that they can manage them for their own interests.
But even when evidence of this type of abuse becomes evident, new places for abuse are created repeatedly - take the American repeal of the Glass Steagall Act, which separated commercial from investments.
We have repeatedly witnessed the consequences of the excesses of unimpeded market liberation.
We must now resist the temptation to lean towards the other extreme.
The challenge to be met is to achieve the right balance.
